data.name: ToolTipGrowerToFinishProductionSystem
data.value: Grower-to-finish operations house feeder hogs until they are marketed at ~110-115 kg live weight. These operations do not keep breeding animals but purchase their pigs from weaner operations.

data.name: ToolTipFarrowToWeanProductionSystem
data.value: Farrow-to-wean operations house sows, gilts and possibly boars; these operations maintain the breeding stock but sell piglets to iso-wean or grower-to-finish operations.

data.name: ToolTipIsoWeanProductionSystem
data.value: Iso-wean (isolated wean) operations are also called ‘nursery barns’, and house piglets that have been weaned at ~18-28 days old. These animals are kept in isolation from sows and larger hogs to prevent disease transmission. Hogs typically spend 5-8 weeks in a nursery barn, although it can be as little as 2 weeks.

data.name: TooltipRotationComponent
data.value: A component to create a crop rotation. A single crop rotation component can be used instead of multiple field components.

data.name: ToolTipFarrowToFinishProductionSystem
data.value: Farrow-to-finish operations keep and mate sows, farrow litters and raise piglets to market weight.

data.name: ToolTipPulletFarm
data.value: Juvenile females (pullets) are transported from hatcheries to pullet farms or to pullet barns on egg production operations where they remain until they reach breeding age (approximately 18-20 weeks), after which they are moved to egg laying operations/barns.

data.name: ToolTipChickenMultiplierBreeder
data.value: Represents the reproduction portion of bird production where birds that produce eggs for reproduction are managed; these eggs are then sent to reproduction hatcheries to be hatched. In the multiplier breeder operation, adult males and females are housed together.

data.name: ToolTipChickenEggProduction
data.value: A component for pullets that reach approximately 18-20 weeks of age and are transferred from either separate pullet operations or pullet barns on an egg production operation to egg-laying barns. These hens will produce eggs for up to 71 weeks of age.

data.name: ToolTipTurkeyMultiplierBreeder
data.value: Represents the reproduction portion of bird production where birds that produce eggs for reproduction are managed; these eggs are then sent to reproduction hatcheries to be hatched. In the multiplier breeder operation, male and female turkeys are housed separately for the entire life cycle.

data.name: ToolTipChickenMultiplierHatchery
data.value: Hatcheries receive fertile eggs from multiplier breeder farms, hatch them and then deliver the hatchlings (day old chicks or poults) to pullet farms (female chicks only), to pullet barns on egg-laying operations, or to meat production operations (male and female chicks, for chicken and/or turkey).

data.name: ToolTipTurkeyMeatProduction
data.value: Poults arriving in the operation from a multiplier hatchery are raised to market weight after approximately 12 weeks (turkey broilers) or 16-22 weeks (heavy turkeys)

data.name: ToolTipChickenMeatProduction
data.value: Chicks arriving in the operation from a multiplier hatchery are raised to market weight (1-4 kg, depending on bird type and end product) after approximately 30-56 days (depending on the bird type and rearing system).

data.name: AnaerobicDigestionStepOneText
data.value:
All digestate produced by the anaerobic digestor is separated into liquid and solid amounts by default. To keep the digestate in a non-separated (raw) state, disable this function by selecting the "No" option below.
Please note: Holos assumes that all digestate (separated and non-separated) available for land application has not undergone a period of post-digester storage and is thus 'raw' digestate.

data.name: AnaerobicDigestionStepTwoText
data.value:
All manure produced by animals on the farm can be added to the anaerobic digestor. Choose which management periods will be selected as the source of manure entering the digestor. To select a management period, click the "Add" checkbox. By default, all daily manure (100%) produced by the selected management period is added to the digestor. This daily percentage amount can be adjusted as needed by adjusting the "Daily manure added to digestor" column.
If no animals exist on the farm, it is possible to use imported manure as a feedstock for the digestor. To add imported manure, the user must enter a daily amount fed into the digestor and the manure type.

data.name: AnaerobicDigestionStepThreeText

data.name: NumberOfRestDaysInCycleDescription
data.value: For each animal group, a single default production cycle (composed of one or more management periods) is provided in the table below. A number of rest (non-productive) days between production cycles can be entered if there is more than one production cycle per year.

data.name: TooltipProductionDays
data.value:
In Canada, some livestock production systems are typically "all in, all out" systems, where all animals enter and leave the barn at the same time with a number of days between production periods to clean the facilities before the next group of animals arrives.
These systems include feedlot cattle (steers and heifers), swine, and poultry production. Therefore, to calculate total annual emissions from a livestock operation where there are multiple production cycles per year, the number of production days per year (excluding non-productive days between production cycles) are considered.
Daily emissions estimates are multipled by the total number of production days in a year.

data.name: MessageAnnualDetailedReportMessage
data.value:
Annual Holos estimates for the livestock components represent the sum of monthly emissions for a single production cycle only (as defined by the model user on the Component Selection screen). Therefore, if one or more animal groups have more than one production cycle in a calendar year, multiply the results by the number of production cycles in a year to get an estimate of actual yearly emissions related to housing and manure management/storage.
Please note: emissions related to the deposition or application of livestock manure to a field are reported under the relevant field or rotation component.
Please note: for each field component, the annual emissions in this report represent the total emissions from all synthetic fertilizer applied and all crop residues for the relevant calendar year, but include manure-related emissions for a single production cycle only.

data.name: MessageMonthlyDetailedReportMessage
data.value:
Monthly Holos estimates for the livestock components represent monthly estimates are for a single production cycle only. Therefore, to get an annual emissions value for these components, multiply the results by the number of production cycles in a year.
Please note: emissions related to the deposition or application of livestock manure to a field are reported under the relevant field or rotation component.
